urnals, travel journalism, advertisements and cinematic and literary representations, it charts the rise of hotel culture from 1870 to 1939. From Henry James to Elizabeth Bowen and Charlie Chaplin, from the ecstatic Waldorf to the ephemeral Ritz, from upstate New York to the Italian Riviera, the book considers the effects of hotel space on bodies, selves and communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCivilization, Modern. 0aHotels in literature. 0aHotels in motion pictures. 0aHotelsxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aHotelsxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in literature. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in motion pictures. 0aSpace (Architecture) in literature. 0aSpace (Architecture) in motion pictures. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107804060 cprintz978147445665440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147445667840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474456678423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474456678/original  a978-3-11-078040-6  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK